name: 2,4-dichloro-3-nitrophenol
Reason: The target compound 2,4-dichloro-3-nitrophenol consists of a phenol basic unit with additional substituents that affect its melting point. The basic phenol has a melting point of approximately 41°C. Chloro groups typically increase the melting point due to their effect on molecular symmetry and dipole interactions, with ortho and para substitutions having a greater effect than meta substitutions. Considering there are two chloro groups, one at the ortho and one at the para position relative to the hydroxy group, each might contribute an increase of about 20°C to the melting point. The nitro group is an electron-withdrawing group that creates a stronger hydrogen bond due to the resultant increase in the acidity of the hydroxy group and contributes significantly to the melting point. Its presence at the meta position has a lesser effect on melting point compared to ortho and para substitutions, but it can still contribute towards an increase in melting point, accounting for an expected increase of around 25°C. Taken together, the effects of the substituents are additive.
